nsport, you can just do the following search-and-replace: NioEventLoopGroup</c\n---match---\n 0 0 1-.018 1.042.751.751 0 0 1-1.042.018 1.998 1.998 0 0 0-2.83 0l-2.5 2.5a1.998 1.998 0 0 0 0 2.83Z\"> Because the native transport is compatible with the NIO transport, you can just do the following search-and-replace: NioEventLoopGroup → EpollEventLoopGroup NioEventLoop → EpollEventLoop NioServerSocketChannel → EpollServerSocketChannel NioSocketChannel → EpollSocketChannel Because the native transport is not part of the Netty core, you need to pull the netty-transport-native-epoll as a dependency in your Maven pom.xml , or equivalent for your build system: < dependencies >\n < dependency >\n < groupId >io.netty</ groupId >\n < artifactId >netty-transport-native-epoll</ artifactId >\n < version >${project.version}</ version >\n < classifier >linux-x86_64</ classifier >\n </ dependency >\n \n---match---\nlace: NioEventLoopGroup → EpollEventLoopGroup NioEventLoop → EpollEventLoop NioServerSocketChannel → EpollServerSocketChannel NioSocketChannel → EpollSocketChannel Because the native transport is not part of the Netty core, you need to pull the netty-transport-native-epoll as a dependency in your Maven pom.xml , or equivalent for your build system: < dependencies >\n < dependency >\n < groupId >io.netty</ groupId >\n < artifactId >netty-transport-native-epoll</ artifactId >\n < version >${project.version}</ version >\n < classifier >linux-x86_64</ classifier >\n </ dependency >\n ...\n </ dependencies > In the above, the classifier is linux-x86_64 , which means the native binaries included in the dependency are compiled for Linux, running on 64-bit x86 \n---match---\n → EpollServerSocketChannel NioSocketChannel → EpollSocketChannel Because the native transport is not part of the Netty core, you need to pull the netty-transport-native-epoll as a dependency in your Maven pom.xml , or equivalent for your build system: < dependencies >\n < dependency >\n < groupId >io.netty</ groupId >\n < artifactId >netty-transport-native-epoll</ artifactId >\n < version >${project.version}</ version >\n < classifier >linux-x86_64</ classifier >\n </ dependency >\n ...\n </ dependencies > In the above, the classifier is linux-x86_64 , which means the native binaries included in the dependency are compiled for Linux, running on 64-bit x86 CPUs. Other CPU architectures, and some specific Linux distributions, will need different classifiers. Note: The official Linux builds are all linked against GLIBC. This means\n---match---\nel NioSocketChannel → EpollSocketChannel Because the native transport is not part of the Netty core, you need to pull the netty-transport-native-epoll as a dependency in your Maven pom.xml , or equivalent for your build system: < dependencies >\n < dependency >\n < groupId >io.netty</ groupId >\n < artifactId >netty-transport-native-epoll</ artifactId >\n < version >${project.version}</ version >\n < classifier >linux-x86_64</ classifier >\n </ dependency >\n ...\n </ dependencies > In the above, the classifier is linux-x86_64 , which means the native binaries included in the dependency are compiled for Linux, running on 64-bit x86 CPUs. Other CPU architectures, and some specific Linux distributions, will need different classifiers. Note: The official Linux builds are all linked against GLIBC. This means operating systems that use Mus\n---match---\nde>NioSocketChannel → EpollSocketChannel Because the native transport is not part of the Netty core, you need to pull the netty-transport-native-epoll as a dependency in your Maven pom.xml , or equivalent for your build system: < dependencies >\n < dependency >\n < groupId >io.netty</ groupId >\n < artifactId >netty-transport-native-epoll</ artifactId >\n < version >${project.version}</ version >\n < classifier >linux-x86_64</ classifier >\n </ dependency >\n ...\n </ dependencies > In the above, the classifier is linux-x86_64 , which means the native binaries included in the dependency are compiled for Linux, running on 64-bit x86 CPUs. Other CPU architectures, and some specific Linux distributions, will need different classifiers. Note: The official Linux builds are all linked against GLIBC. This means operating systems that use Musl as their libc implemen\n---match---\nneed to pull the netty-transport-native-epoll as a dependency in your Maven pom.xml , or equivalent for your build system: < dependencies >\n < dependency >\n < groupId >io.netty</ groupId >\n < artifactId >netty-transport-native-epoll</ artifactId >\n < version >${project.version}</ version >\n < classifier >linux-x86_64</ classifier >\n </ dependency >\n ...\n </ dependencies > In the above, the classifier is linux-x86_64 , which means the native binaries included in the dependency are compiled for Linux, running on 64-bit x86 CPUs. Other CPU architectures, and some specific Linux distributions, will need different classifiers. Note: The official Linux builds are all linked against GLIBC. This means operating systems that use Musl as their libc implementation are not supported by the official builds of the Netty native transports. If you wish to use the Netty native transports on unsupporte\n---match---\n/artifactId> <version>${project.version}</version> <classifier>linux-x86_64</classifier> </dependency> ... </dependencies>\"> < dependencies >\n < dependency >\n < groupId >io.netty</ groupId >\n < artifactId >netty-transport-native-epoll</ artifactId >\n < version >${project.version}</ version >\n < classifier >linux-x86_64</ classifier >\n </ dependency >\n ...\n </ dependencies > In the above, the classifier is linux-x86_64 , which means the native binaries included in the dependency are compiled for Linux, running on 64-bit x86 CPUs. Other CPU architectures, and some specific Linux distributions, will need different classifiers. Note: The official Linux builds are all linked against GLIBC. This means operating systems that use Musl as their libc implementation are not supported by the official builds of the Netty native transports. If you wish to use the Netty native transports on unsupported CPU architectures or libc implementations, you will need to make your own build. See below for how to do that. For using the native transport in a sbt project, please add line below to your libraryDependencies : <div class=\"snippet-clipboard-content notranslate position-relative overflow-auto\" data-snippet-clipboard-copy-content='\"io.netty\" \n---match---\n/version> <classifier>linux-x86_64</classifier> </dependency> ... </dependencies>\"> < dependencies >\n < dependency >\n < groupId >io.netty</ groupId >\n < artifactId >netty-transport-native-epoll</ artifactId >\n < version >${project.version}</ version >\n < classifier >linux-x86_64</ classifier >\n </ dependency >\n ...\n </ dependencies > In the above, the classifier is linux-x86_64 , which means the native binaries included in the dependency are compiled for Linux, running on 64-bit x86 CPUs. Other CPU architectures, and some specific Linux distributions, will need different classifiers. Note: The official Linux builds are all linked against GLIBC. This means operating systems that use Musl as their libc implementation are not supported by the official builds of the Netty native transports. If you wish to use the Netty native transports on unsupported CPU architectures or libc implementations, you will need to make your own build. See below for how to do that. For using the native transport in a sbt project, please add line below to your libraryDependencies : <div class=\"snippet-clipboard-content notranslate position-relative overflow-auto\" data-snippet-clipboard-copy-content='\"io.netty\" % \"netty-transport-native-epoll\" % \"${project.version}\" cla\n---match---\nifier> </dependency> ... </dependencies>\"> < dependencies >\n < dependency >\n < groupId >io.netty</ groupId >\n < artifactId >netty-transport-native-epoll</ artifactId >\n < version >${project.version}</ version >\n < clas