[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating dependencies**\n\nI believe this is a single JSON, which seems okay to me. I need to think about the extra Maven dependency, \"netty-transport-native-kqueue:4.2.7.Final.\" The documentation mentions it requires the classifier osx-x86_64, but I wonder if that's concrete evidence that this extra dependency is actually needed. Since the library is classes-only, it seems like to instantiate channels without running into a JNI UnsatisfiedLinkError, we kind of do need the native artifact. But on Ubuntu, without kqueue, is it really all that meaningful?\n\n**Assessing Unix socket creation**\n\nI’m considering how Unix sockets are created using common configurations on Linux. It seems that kqueue isn’t registered until the event loop, which complicates things. If the constructor creates a file descriptor with the Unix common native, it might still work even if kqueue isn’t available. There’s potential to improve coverage here! The documentation indicates some dependencies, so I wonder if we need to signal these in the guidance. Overall, I’m exploring how to manage our dependencies better!\n\n**Clarifying dependency representation**\n\nI'm delving into the representation of dependencies, focusing on the deterministic coordinate field without a classifier. This matter seems significant since it affects how guidance is structured; they should include environment variables and system properties for test setups in the agent guidance. It appears that classifiers aren't meant to be included. I also feel the urge to research the resolved dependencies in actual Gradle configurations to ensure I’m capturing everything accurately. Overall, I want to make sure I'm addressing this properly!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0c3c1a91eaf0c522016a3e61c69ae48193965cb1d8030fab15\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqPmHljIFMqXKAQa3ZncSEN